    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "40c5c3ed_9b7eb556",
        "filename": "buildbucket/appengine/internal/search/query.go",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 110,
      "author": {
        "id": 1398165
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-13T19:25:50Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027m afraid I disagree with this. We\u0027ve discussed a bit in previous CL - https://screenshot.googleplex.com/A63rUpAcxkZ.\n\n1. We cannot just blindly convert from Py version without reasonably redesign. The repo/code structure is different. \nIn Python, we have a `api.py` containing all the APIs handlers (SearchBuilds/GetBuild/ScheduleBuild). Then we have `validation.py` for all validation and `search.py` for the detailed search logic. \n\nHowever in Go, the convention is different. We\u0027ve separated APIs handlers into different files like `Search_builds.go` and `get_build.go` instead of a central `api.go`, and put the further operation logic into the same file.  For example `list_builders.go`, we put the `validateListBuilders()` and detailed list operation `fetchBuilders()` into the same `list_builders.go`, which are called by `ListBuilders()`. \n\nIf we\u0027d like to put `fetch()` logic for SearchBuilds in a different file - query.go as in Python version, why we don\u0027t separate all the validation logic as well?\n\n2. Therefore, I\u0027d like to propose to put the `fetch()` related logic into the `search_builds.go` to be consistent with other RPC go handlers files. And we can rename the `internal/search/query.go` to `internal/model/searchquery.go`(may be a better name) to implies it contains intermediate objects used by this repro. We don\u0027t necessarily binding any DB operation onto those intermediate objects because there are not db model objects.",
      "parentUuid": "e4dcce9b_f80014cd",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 110,
        "startChar": 21,
        "endLine": 110,
        "endChar": 29
      },
      "revId": "aee1718179d23dfb7c9de108320d6b0a39ee9b05",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3e6b7052_f12003ae",
        "filename": "buildbucket/appengine/internal/search/query.go",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 110,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-14T01:25:54Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "1. In Python, a module is one file. In Go, a package is one directory. Python modules are semantically equivalent to Go packages. From this perspective, it is much different: in python we have a single module \"api\" with all RPCs. In Go, we have a single \"rpc\" package with all RPCs. So in Go, file names are not as important as directories. \n\nAs you say, search.Query is not a db model object, so I wouldn\u0027t put it into \"model\" package.\n\nI think I am failing to delivery my point across. Imagine, for whatever reason, we need to call search from another piece of code (not SearchBuilds RPC). If that piece of code also wants to take advantage of both search implementations, it would have to duplicate the logic in SearchBuilds RPCs (switching between the two, falling back to query if tag index is incomplete), etc.\n\nAt the same time, I don\u0027t understand what is the problem with having one function\n\n  func (q *Query) Fetch(ctx context.Context) (*pb.SearchBuildsResponse, error)\n\nthat internally switches between the two impl. It would be usable from search_builds.go just fine.",
      "parentUuid": "40c5c3ed_9b7eb556",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 110,
        "startChar": 21,
        "endLine": 110,
        "endChar": 29
      },
      "revId": "aee1718179d23dfb7c9de108320d6b0a39ee9b05",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
